The write-down of European debts is inevitable.
Berkeley — "That was just the Greek crisis," or "That was just the Greek and Irish crisis," people used to think. But not anymore, because it is now clearly a eurozone crisis.
To deal with it, it is both easier and more difficult than typically anticipated.
The economic rationale for this crisis is quite simple.
The Greek finances are problematic.
There are issues with the banking sector in Ireland.
The private debt market in Portugal has issues.
Spain has issues in all of the above three aspects.
Though the details differ, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to go through a painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency depreciation.
Devaluation would enhance export competitiveness, effectively using external demand to make up for internal demand.
However, these countries are all part of the eurozone and do not have their own independent currencies to devalue externally, so they can only rely on internal depreciation as a substitute.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
Actually, these crisis countries have shown considerable determination to tighten their belts.
However, one economic variable did not change with the adjustment of the others, and that is the debt between the public and private sectors.
The face value of government accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt has remained largely unchanged, except for some debts owed to ordinary junior creditors.
It is this simple fact that makes the internal-devaluation strategy self-contradictory: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes relative to incomes.
The heavier the debt burden, the more it necessitates cutting public spending and increasing taxes in order to address the government’s and its defenders’ (such as banks) debts.
This, in turn, requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the burden of debt, thereby perpetuating the vicious cycle and dragging the economy into a recessionary trap.
Therefore, to make internal debt haircuts effective, we must find ways to reduce the face value of debts.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debts must be converted into equity, and when banks' assets are insufficient to cover their debts, they should be written off.
Mortgage debts also need to be written down.
It is understandable that policymakers do not want to go down this road.
Contracts are sacred.
The government is concerned about losing credibility with financial markets.
If creditors are mainly based overseas, especially in foreign banks, haircuts would only drag down other countries.
These concerns are not without merit, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
There are only two options: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
The leaders of European countries must choose between two options.
They consistently ruled out the option of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation inevitably requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is neither reasonable nor logical.
The operation of debt restructuring is straightforward and simple.
The government can issue a batch of debt instruments with face values discounted by a certain ratio compared to the current debt face values.
Bondholders have the option of either sticking with bonds that are convertible at par value but with later maturity dates and lower interest rates; or accepting discounted bonds with lower face values but earlier maturity dates and higher interest rates.
This is not cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But for it to be successful, there are three prerequisites.
First, assure the bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone needs to come forward to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin American debt restructuring was carried out under the Brady Plan, the United States Treasury played the role of the "guarantor big brother."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, the restructuring of one country would raise expectations for other countries, leading to a contagion effect.
Finally, the balance sheets of banks that incur losses from debt restructuring must be strengthened.
These banks need to undergo genuine stress tests, rather than the ceremonial exercises conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring indicates a capital shortfall, then a comprehensive equity-for-debt swap for the relevant banks’ services should be carried out.
If this is not enough, the government must step in to inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires concerted action from all countries.
Once the banking sector’s balance sheets have been strengthened, it will be possible to restructure mortgages, bank debts, and other private-sector debts without undermining the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires firm leadership.
The leaders in Germany must recognize that the country’s banks have significant exposure to the debt of eurozone perimeter nations, and the situation is urgent.
They must convince both the backroom bosses and voters that mobilizing public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt such a strategy, it should be willing to shoulder the responsibility for the guarantees.
In other words, the leaders of Europe, particularly those in Germany, need to make the consequences sound more severe – or else disaster is looming.
Because that is the fact.
